==Chinese==

===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{Han compound|仌|水|alt1=冫|c1=p|c2=s|ls=psc}}. {{och-l|*冫}} is the original pictogram for this character, a semantic {{och-l|*水}} was added later.

The above vulgar character in ''Shuowen Jiezi'' is {{l|zh|凝|tr=-}}.

===Etymology 1===
{{zh-forms|alt=仌,冫,氷,𣲝,𨻱,𣲙,仒,𫥇}}
From {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*l-pəm||to freeze; snow}} (provisionally reconstructed). Compare {{cog|sit-tan-pro|*pam||snow}}, {{cog|sit-jap|jpɣom||to freeze}}, {{m|sit-jap|tɤjpɣom||ice}}, and perhaps {{cog|txg|𘒓||to congeal}} (STEDT; {{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}; {{zh-ref|Zhang, Jacques, and Lai, 2019}}; {{zh-ref|Jacques, 2014}}).

Within Chinese, {{och-l|凌|ice}} and possibly {{och-l|凝|id=1|to congeal}} are usually considered cognates (STEDT; {{zh-ref|Zhengzhang, 2003}}; {{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}; {{zh-ref|Baxter and Sagart, 2014}}). However, they are phonologically difficult to reconcile with the {{cog|tbq}} cognates above (cf. {{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).

STEDT also includes {{och-l|雱|heavy (snowfall)}} and {{och-l|霙|snowflake}} in the Chinese comparandum of (what it reconstructs) {{cog|sit-pro|*r-pəm|*r-p(w)am}}.

Alternatively, this may be related to {{cog|okz|ប្រិង៑|t=to harden; to solidify}}, from {{m|okz|រិង៑|t=to dry up}}, although the meanings are difficult to reconcile ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).

